framework for Wolfson’s examination is the rabbinic teaching that the word emet, "truth," comprises the first, middle, and last letters of the Hebrew alphabet, alef, mem, and tau, which serve, in turn, as semiotic signposts for the three tenses of time—past, present, and future. By heeding the letters of emet we discern the truth of time manifestly concealed in the time of truth, the beginning that cannot begin if it is to be the beginning, the middle that re/marks the place of origin and destiny, and the end that is the figuration of the impossible disclosing the impossibility of figuration, the finitude of death that facilitates the possibility of rebirth. The time of death does not mark the death of time, but time immortal, the moment of truth that bestows on the truth of the moment an endless beginning of a beginningless end, the truth of death encountered incessantly in retracing steps of time yet to be taken—between, before, beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCabalaxHistory. 0aTimexPhilosophy. 0aTimexReligious aspectsxJudaism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aaqiva.  aazriel of gerona.  aazriel.  ababylonian talmud.  abahir.  abahiric text.  aberakhah.  abereshit.  abinah.  abuddhism.  adeath.  adestiny.  aeastern philosophy.  aeastern religion.  aemet.  aesoteric religion.  aimmortality.  aislam.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  akabbalah.  akabbalism.  amedieval kabbalah.  amysticism.  anature of time.  aphilosophy.  arebirth.  areligion.  areligious studies.  asemiotics.  atemporality.  atime.  awestern philosophy.  ayiddishkeit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024619540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093231940uhttps://ww